draw((0,0)--(1,0)--(1.5,.5*sqrt(3))--(1,sqrt(3))--(0,sqrt(3))--(-.5,.5*sqrt(3))--cycle);
draw((1,0)--(0,sqrt(3)));
[/asy] Now we draw in the other two long diagonals.  We have split the hexagon into six equilateral triangles, which are congruent by symmetry.  [asy]
size(80);
draw((0,0)--(1,0)--(1.5,.5*sqrt(3))--(1,sqrt(3))--(0,sqrt(3))--(-.5,.5*sqrt(3))--cycle);
draw((1,0)--(0,sqrt(3))); draw((1.5,.5*sqrt(3))--(-.5,.5*sqrt(3))); draw((1,sqrt(3))--(0,0));
[/asy] We see that two side lengths make up one long diagonal.  Let the hexagon's side length be $s$, then, its long diagonal has length $2s$ and its perimeter has length $6s$.  The ratio of its long diagonal to its perimeter is hence $\frac{2s}{6s}=\boxed{\frac{1}{3}}$.

We can line up the numbers and subtract just as we do in base 10.  For example, when we borrow from the $3^1$s place, the digit 1 in the units place becomes $4$, while the digit in the $3^1$s place decreases by 1. Continuing in this way, we find $$\begin{array}{c@{}c@{}c@{}c@{}c}
& \cancelto{1}{2} & \cancelto{4}{1} & \cancelto{1}{2} & \cancelto{4}{1}_3 \\
-& & 2 & 1 & 2_3 \\
\cline{2-5}
& 1 & 2 & 0 & 2_3 \\
\end{array}$$So the difference is $\boxed{1202_3}$.

